at Makes Clusters Competitive? tests fundamental theoretical hypotheses about what makes industries competitive in a globalized world by using the wine industries of several countries as case studies: Extremadura (Spain), Tuscany (Italy), South Australia, Chile, and British Columbia (Canada), Taking into account historical and location-specific characteristics, and drawing out policy lessons for other regions that would like to promote their industries, this volume demonstrates the value of applying cluster theory to understand market forces, while also describing the forces underlying the development of the wine industry in a range of different settings. An excellent resource for those interested in what makes industries succeed or struggle, What Makes Clusters Competitive? offers guidance for policymakers and the private sector on how to promote local industries. Contributors include David Aylward, Alexis Bwenge, Sara Daniele, F.J. Mesías Díaz, Christian Felzenstein, Husam Gabreldar, F. Pulido García, Sarah Giest, Elisa Giuliani, Andy Hira, Mike Howlett, A.F. Pulido Moreno, and Oriana Perrone.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCompetitionvCase studies. 0aIndustrial clustersvCase studies. 0aWine industryvCase studies. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Development / General.2bisacsh1 aAylward, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBwenge, Alexis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaniele, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aF.Pulido, Angel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFelzensztein, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGabreldar, Husam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiest, Sarah, econtributor.